        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1403.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Erasmus Alvey Darwin, 19 April 1851</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See the second <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1401.xml">letter to Emma Darwin, [18 April 1851]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Hannah was a servant of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5010.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Fanny Mackintosh</ref> Wedgwood (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1424.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Fanny Mackintosh Wedgwood, 28 [April 1851]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Leith Hill Place, near Dorking, Surrey, was the home of Caroline and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5027.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Josiah Wedgwood III</ref>. Henrietta Darwin and the children of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5010.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Fanny Mackintosh</ref> Wedgwood stayed there while CD and Fanny nursed Anne in Malvern.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5019.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hensleigh Wedgwood</ref> was Emma’s brother and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5010.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Fanny Mackintosh</ref> Wedgwood’s husband. Fanny remained with CD to help look after Anne. Some nine years previously, when Fanny had been exhausted by her new baby and was nursing <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5019.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hensleigh Wedgwood</ref> through a dangerous illness, Emma had looked after her older children at Down (Wedgwood and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8245.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Wedgwood 1980</ref>, pp. 246–7).</note>
        </div>        
            
